<br>
Well, of course I disagree...<br>
<br>
Hehe I know my apples from my oranges, thank you, and your comment, though more subtle, fits within the context of the arguement you wove to villify my comments as personal attacks.<br>
<br>
I was purposeful in stating that Shintou's position was intolerant because, quite frankly, it was.  Telling people to pack up and leave because they fall into a certain category is far more egregious than calling them a &quot;turd&quot; or a &quot;madman&quot;.  Intolerance has no business being in EQ, let alone RL for that matter, and I felt I had to put up a sign and label it, perhaps for reasons similar to those that lead you to defend Shintou.<br>
<br>
Do I think Shin is a &quot;mentally defective&quot; or an intolerant ass in RL - far from it!  He is clearly an imaginative and passionate fella.  However as his statements become louder and more profane, it's only natural that his opponents cranked up the volume as well.<br>
<br>
As the threads progressed, some of his comments (on the anti-non-rp side) became far too volatile as did the counter-statements.  I do feel that you are using the &quot;slippery-slope&quot; tactic of drawing my comments down to the level of personal attacks.  If I stated that Shin was a fanatical rp-nazi, of course that is branding him directly and all that he says on the subject.  In contrast however, his statements were intolerant and anti-social - they left little or no room for discussion.  <br>
<br>
You used the &quot;American thinking&quot; axiom as a means to conduct a &quot;discursive analysis&quot; on my claims that Shin's comments were &quot;comparable racism&quot;.  <br>
<br>
First, jumping to the word racism (which did appear in my post) is sensationalist - there is a distinct difference between intolerance (which did apply) and racism (which did not apply) and I was very clear on that within the thread.  <br>
<br>
Second, would your means of discursive analysis seem so legitimate and inoffensive if I had used a &quot;Stalinist thinking&quot; model to analyse Shin's comments?  In that circumstance, you might be quick to state that such a reference is a &quot;personal attack&quot;.  The only difference is the sensationality of the point of reference...the mechanics, and aim, of the literary device however are the same:  i.e. Stalinst thinking = oppressive therefore your comments = oppressive...American thinking regarding freedom = flawed therefore your comments on freedom of expression = flawed.<br>
<br>
In truth, all comments aimed at an individual's thoughts and statements *could* be patternized as personal attacks using the slippery-slope apparatus.  The steps elevating counter-arguements above the baseness of personal attacks however, are formed from tact and subtlety.  There are times, however, where certain statements should be labelled bluntly.  And, that's what I did.<br>
<br>
Rexfelix<br>
Agent of the Balance<br>
